========================================
TDD RULES - MANDATORY COMPLIANCE
========================================

## CORE TDD PRINCIPLES

1. Tests MUST compile successfully
   - dotnet build MUST pass
   - Compilation errors are NOT acceptable
   - Failing tests must be runtime failures, not build errors

2. RED phase definition
   - Tests FAIL due to missing logic only
   - NOT due to missing types, compile errors, or broken references

3. STRICT TDD FLOW (MANDATORY)
   Step 1: Write test (must compile)
   Step 2: Run test -> FAIL (logic only)
   Step 3: Implement minimal code to PASS
   Step 4: Refactor
   DO NOT skip any step
   DO NOT implement before test runs

## FORBIDDEN (CRITICAL VIOLATIONS)

- DO NOT use Entity Framework in unit tests
- DO NOT use DbContext or DbSet
- DO NOT connect to database
- DO NOT call external APIs or services
- DO NOT access file system or network
- DO NOT redefine framework classes (DbSet, DbContext, etc.)
- DO NOT create tests that do not compile
- DO NOT tightly couple tests to infrastructure
- DO NOT depend on VanAn.Shared.Domain in unit tests
- DO NOT depend on VanAn.CoreHub.Services in unit tests

If any violation occurs -> STOP immediately and report

## REQUIRED ARCHITECTURE (MANDATORY)

1. Use PURE DOMAIN MODELS (test-friendly)
   - Create minimal versions of entities:
     - Lead
     - FacebookLead
     - CustomerOnboarding
   - Only include properties required by tests
   - DO NOT wait for full implementation

2. Use INTERFACE-FIRST DESIGN
   - Define interfaces BEFORE implementation
   - Example:
     public interface ILeadRepository
     {
         Task AddAsync(Lead lead);
         Task<Lead?> GetByIdAsync(Guid id);
     }

3. Use TEST DOUBLES (IN-MEMORY)
   - Replace all infrastructure with fake implementations
   - Example:
     public class InMemoryLeadRepository : ILeadRepository
     {
         private readonly List<Lead> _data = new();
         public Task AddAsync(Lead lead)
         {
             _data.Add(lead);
             return Task.CompletedTask;
         }
         public Task<Lead?> GetByIdAsync(Guid id)
         {
             return Task.FromResult(_data.FirstOrDefault(x => x.Id == id));
         }
     }

4. TEST ISOLATION
   - Each test must be independent
   - No shared state
   - Always use fresh in-memory instances

5. TEST PROJECT INDEPENDENCE
   - Test project MUST build without full implementation
   - MUST NOT depend on Infrastructure layer
   - MUST NOT require real database or services

## ARCHITECTURE BOUNDARY

- Unit Tests -> Domain + Application ONLY
- Integration Tests -> Infrastructure (separate project)
- DO NOT mix layers

## EXECUTION POLICY

- On any violation:
  -> STOP immediately
  -> Explain root cause
  -> Fix using TDD principles
- Priority:
  1. TDD correctness
  2. Clean architecture
  3. THEN speed

## SUCCESS CRITERIA

- Test project builds successfully
- No compilation errors
- Tests execute normally
- Tests FAIL only due to missing logic
- No infrastructure dependency in unit tests

## CURRENT STATUS

- Phase 1: Design Complete
- Phase 2: Test Cases Complete (TDD-compliant)
- Phase 3: Test Execution (RED phase working)
- Phase 4: Implementation (GREEN phase pending)

## NEXT STEPS

1. Implement GREEN phase for FacebookLeadService
2. Continue with other services
3. Maintain TDD compliance throughout

